Western Sabah in Borneo has a mountainous terrain, which includes the Mount Kinabalu as part of the Crocker Range and the Mount Trus Madi of the Trusmadi Range. Many species of orthopterans have been documented from these mountain ranges, even in very recent times (e.g.,
;
;
). Our field sampling in 2023 had also led to the discovery of new species of crickets (
,
). Here we focus on the katydids from the tribes Agraeciini and Meconematini of the subfamilies Conocephalinae and Meconematinae , respectively.

The specimens were first preserved in absolute analytical-grade ethanol and later pinned and dry-preserved. The sclerotized parts of the male genitalia, whenever present, were dissected from softened specimens, then cleaned using aqueous KOH and subsequently preserved in hand sanitiser. Morphological features were imaged with a Canon EOS 700D digital SLR camera with a macro photo lens MP-E 
65 mm
f/2.8 USM (1–5×). Canon Macro Twin Lite MT-24EX was also used for lighting and flash. Image editing was accomplished using Adobe Photoshop CC 2014 (Adobe Systems Incorporated, San Jose, CA, 
USA
). Measurements of dried-pinned specimen were made from images using ImageJ 1.51j8 (Wayne Rasband, Research Services Branch, National Institute of Mental Health, Bethesda, MD, 
USA
). For the measurements, the following abbreviations are used: BL = body length; BWL = body with wing length; HW = head width (eye tip–eye tip); 
PL
= pronotum length; 
PW
= pronotum width (maximum); TL = tegmen length; TW = tegmen width (maximum); HFL = hind (posterior) femur length; HFW = hind (posterior) femur width (maximum); HTL = hind (posterior) tibia length; OL = ovipositor length; OW = ovipositor width (maximum).

